<subSubSection id="C30D654BFF8CFFA89A35FF65F86131D4" pageId="29" pageNumber="30" type="description">
<paragraph id="8BA836C0FF8CFFA89A35FF65F86131D4" blockId="29.[151,1437,150,1041]" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">
Giant Devilray or 
<emphasis id="B963EAD2FF8CFFA89B6AFF64F9BE30B4" bold="true" box="[791,1023,150,177]" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">Spinetail Devil Ray</emphasis>
. 
<bibRefCitation id="EF864B31FF8CFFA89C73FF65FFDD30B4" author="Notarbartolo di Sciara" box="[1038,1436,151,177]" etAl="et al." firstAuthor="Notarbartolo di Sciara" pageId="29" pageNumber="30" pagination="4" refId="ref305876" refString="Notarbartolo di Sciara, G., Stevens, G. &amp; Fernando, D. (2020) The giant devil ray Mobula mobular (Bonnaterre, 1788) is not giant, but it is the only spinetail devil ray. Marine Biodiversity Records, 13, 4. https: // doi. org / 10.1186 / s 41200 - 020 - 00187 - 0" type="journal article" year="2020">
Notarbartolo di Sciara 
<emphasis id="B963EAD2FF8CFFA89D6CFF65FF0B30B4" box="[1297,1354,151,177]" italics="true" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">et al.</emphasis>
(2020)
</bibRefCitation>
note that recent taxonomic changes among the 
<taxonomicName id="4C174D43FF8CFFA89A9EFF49F91D30D0" authorityName="Gill" authorityYear="1893" box="[739,860,187,213]" class="Elasmobranchii" family="Mobulidae" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Myliobatiformes" pageId="29" pageNumber="30" phylum="Chordata" rank="family">Mobulidae</taxonomicName>
have made the name Giant Devilray obsolete and suggest that Spinetail Devil Ray is more accurate. To at least 
<quantity id="4CEF9B25FF8CFFA89B22FF2CF9DC30FC" box="[863,925,222,249]" metricMagnitude="0" metricUnit="m" metricValue="5.2" pageId="29" pageNumber="30" unit="m" value="5.2">5.2 m</quantity>
(
<quantity id="4CEF9B25FF8CFFA89BD7FF2DF9B530FF" box="[938,1012,223,250]" metricMagnitude="0" metricUnit="m" metricValue="5.21208" pageId="29" pageNumber="30" unit="ft" value="17.1">17.1 ft</quantity>
) DW (
<bibRefCitation id="EF864B31FF8CFFA89C46FF2DFEAB30FF" author="Last, P. R. &amp; Naylor, G. J. P. &amp; Manjaji-Matsumoto, B. M." box="[1083,1258,223,250]" pageId="29" pageNumber="30" pagination="345 - 368" refId="ref293982" refString="Last, P. R., Naylor, G. J. P. &amp; Manjaji-Matsumoto, B. M. (2016 a) A revised classification of the family Dasyatidae (Chondrichthyes: Myliobatiformes) based on new morphological and molecular insights. Zootaxa, 4139, 345 - 368. https: // doi. org / 10.11646 / zootaxa. 4139.3.2" type="journal article" year="2016">
Last 
<emphasis id="B963EAD2FF8CFFA89C0FFF2DFEE930FC" box="[1138,1192,223,249]" italics="true" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">et al.</emphasis>
2016
</bibRefCitation>
). Circumglobal; western Pacific Ocean north to 
<collectingCountry id="F3007650FF8CFFA89A5DFEF1F8253118" box="[544,612,259,285]" name="South Korea" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">Korea</collectingCountry>
and northern 
<collectingCountry id="F3007650FF8CFFA89A83FEF1F97F3118" box="[766,830,259,285]" name="Japan" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">Japan</collectingCountry>
(as 
<taxonomicName id="4C174D43FF8CFFA89B17FEF1FF653118" authority=", Aonuma and Yoshino" authorityName="Aonuma and Yoshino" box="[874,1316,259,285]" class="Elasmobranchii" family="Myliobatidae" genus="Mobula" kingdom="Animalia" order="Myliobatiformes" pageId="29" pageNumber="30" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="japonica">
<emphasis id="B963EAD2FF8CFFA89B17FEF1FE683119" box="[874,1065,259,285]" italics="true" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">Mobula japonica</emphasis>
, Aonuma and Yoshino
</taxonomicName>
in 
<bibRefCitation id="EF864B31FF8CFFA89D38FEF1FB423144" author="Nakabo" firstAuthor="Nakabo" pageId="29" pageNumber="30" refId="ref304533" refString="Nakabo, T. (Ed.). (2002) Fishes of Japan with Pictorial Keys to the Species. Tokai University Press, Tokyo." type="book" year="2002">Nakabo 2002</bibRefCitation>
); central California to Peru (
<bibRefCitation id="EF864B31FF8CFFA89A28FED5F89B3144" author="Ebert" box="[597,730,295,321]" firstAuthor="Ebert" pageId="29" pageNumber="30" refId="ref276228" refString="Ebert, D. A. (2003) Sharks, Rays, and Chimaeras of California. University of California Press, Berkeley." type="book" year="2003">Ebert 2003</bibRefCitation>
), including Gulf of California (
<bibRefCitation id="EF864B31FF8CFFA89C36FED5FFD13147" author="Galvan-Magana" box="[1099,1424,295,322]" etAl="et al." firstAuthor="Galvan-Magana" pageId="29" pageNumber="30" pagination="295 - 311" refId="ref281515" refString="Galvan-Magana, F., Abitia-Cardenas, L. A., Rodriguez-Romero, J., Perez-Espana, H. &amp; Chavez-Ramos, H. (1996) Systematic list of the fishes from Cerralvo Island, Baja California Sur, Mexico. Ciencias Marinas, 22, 295 - 311." type="journal article" year="1996">
Galván-Magaña 
<emphasis id="B963EAD2FF8CFFA89D70FED5FF083144" box="[1293,1353,295,321]" italics="true" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">et al.</emphasis>
1996
</bibRefCitation>
). Depth: surface to at 
<quantity id="4CEF9B25FF8CFFA899DBFEB9FBAD3160" box="[422,492,331,357]" metricMagnitude="2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="7.0" pageId="29" pageNumber="30" unit="m" value="700.0">700 m</quantity>
(
<quantity id="4CEF9B25FF8CFFA89984FEB9F8123163" box="[505,595,331,358]" metricMagnitude="2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="6.998208" pageId="29" pageNumber="30" unit="ft" value="2296.0">2,296 ft</quantity>
) (min.: 
<bibRefCitation id="EF864B31FF8CFFA89AD6FEB9F9693160" author="Ebert" box="[683,808,331,357]" firstAuthor="Ebert" pageId="29" pageNumber="30" refId="ref276228" refString="Ebert, D. A. (2003) Sharks, Rays, and Chimaeras of California. University of California Press, Berkeley." type="book" year="2003">Ebert 2003</bibRefCitation>
; max.: 
<bibRefCitation id="EF864B31FF8CFFA89B05FEB9FE753163" author="Weigmann" box="[888,1076,331,358]" firstAuthor="Weigmann" pageId="29" pageNumber="30" pagination="837 - 1037" refId="ref332578" refString="Weigmann, S. (2016) Annotated checklist of the living sharks, batoids and chimaeras (Chondrichthyes) of the world, with a focus on biogeographical diversity. Journal of Fish Biology, 88, 837 - 1037. https: // doi. org / 10.1111 / jfb. 12874" type="journal article" year="2016">Weigmann 2016</bibRefCitation>
). The 
<taxonomicName id="4C174D43FF8CFFA89C0BFEB9FF783160" baseAuthorityName="Lloyd" baseAuthorityYear="1908" box="[1142,1337,331,357]" class="Elasmobranchii" family="Myliobatidae" genus="Mobula" kingdom="Animalia" order="Myliobatiformes" pageId="29" pageNumber="30" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="thurstoni">
<emphasis id="B963EAD2FF8CFFA89C0BFEB9FF783160" box="[1142,1337,331,357]" italics="true" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">Mobula thurstoni</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
reported by 
<bibRefCitation id="EF864B31FF8CFFA89896FE9DFBFE318C" author="MacGinitie" box="[235,447,367,393]" firstAuthor="MacGinitie" pageId="29" pageNumber="30" pagination="276 - 278" refId="ref298382" refString="MacGinitie, G. E. (1947) Notes on the devilfish, Mobula lucasana, and its parasites. Copeia, 1947, 276 - 278." type="journal article" year="1947">MacGinitie (1947)</bibRefCitation>
from Laguna Beach, southern California is likely 
<taxonomicName id="4C174D43FF8CFFA89C78FE9DFB4B31A8" authority="(Notarbartolo di Sciara 1987)" baseAuthorityName="Notarbartolo di Sciara" baseAuthorityYear="1987" class="Elasmobranchii" family="Myliobatidae" genus="Mobula" kingdom="Animalia" order="Myliobatiformes" pageId="29" pageNumber="30" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="mobular">
<emphasis id="B963EAD2FF8CFFA89C78FE9DFECD318C" box="[1029,1164,367,393]" italics="true" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">M. mobular</emphasis>
(Notarbartolo di Sciara 1987)
</taxonomicName>
. We follow 
<bibRefCitation id="EF864B31FF8CFFA899E9FE61F8D731A8" author="Poortvliet" box="[404,662,402,429]" etAl="et al." firstAuthor="Poortvliet" pageId="29" pageNumber="30" pagination="72 - 85" refId="ref313879" refString="Poortvliet, M., Olsen, J. L., Croll, D. A., Bernardi, G., Newton, K., Kollias, S., O'Sullivan, J., Fernando, D., Stevens, G., Galvan Magana, F., Seret, B., Wintner, S. &amp; Hoarau, G. (2015) A dated molecular phylogeny of manta and devil rays (Mobulidae) based on mitogenome and nuclear sequences. Molecular Phylogenetics and Evolution, 83, 72 - 85. https: // doi. org / 10.1016 / j. ympev. 2014.10.012" type="journal article" year="2015">
Poortvliet 
<emphasis id="B963EAD2FF8CFFA89A77FE61F80531A8" box="[522,580,403,429]" italics="true" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">et al.</emphasis>
(2015)
</bibRefCitation>
and 
<bibRefCitation id="EF864B31FF8CFFA89AB2FE61F9D231AB" author="Last, P. R. &amp; Naylor, G. J. P. &amp; Manjaji-Matsumoto, B. M." box="[719,915,403,430]" pageId="29" pageNumber="30" pagination="345 - 368" refId="ref293982" refString="Last, P. R., Naylor, G. J. P. &amp; Manjaji-Matsumoto, B. M. (2016 a) A revised classification of the family Dasyatidae (Chondrichthyes: Myliobatiformes) based on new morphological and molecular insights. Zootaxa, 4139, 345 - 368. https: // doi. org / 10.11646 / zootaxa. 4139.3.2" type="journal article" year="2016">
Last 
<emphasis id="B963EAD2FF8CFFA89B7AFE61F90131A8" box="[775,832,403,429]" italics="true" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">et al.</emphasis>
(2016)
</bibRefCitation>
in synonymizing 
<taxonomicName id="4C174D43FF8CFFA89C1DFE61FB1931D4" authority="(Muller &amp; Henle, 1841)" baseAuthorityName="Muller &amp; Henle" baseAuthorityYear="1841" class="Elasmobranchii" family="Myliobatidae" genus="Mobula" kingdom="Animalia" order="Myliobatiformes" pageId="29" pageNumber="30" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="japanica">
<emphasis id="B963EAD2FF8CFFA89C1DFE61FF6031A9" box="[1120,1313,403,429]" italics="true" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">Mobula japanica</emphasis>
(Müller &amp; Henle, 1841)
</taxonomicName>
with this species.
</paragraph>
